# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: graphql-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:graphql-security/application-programming-interface] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In computing, a **denial-of-service attack** (**DoS attack** /dɒs/ *doss*) is a cyberattack in which the perpetrator seeks to make a machine or network resource unavailable to its intended users by temporarily or indefinitely disrupting services of a host connected to a network.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Denial of service is typically accomplished by flooding the targeted machine or resource with superfluous requests in an attempt to overload systems and prevent some or all legitimate requests from being fulfilled.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The range of attacks varies widely, spanning from inundating a server with millions of requests to slow its performance, overwhelming a server with a substantial amount of invalid data, to submitting requests with an illegitimate IP address.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In a **distributed denial-of-service attack** (**DDoS attack** /ˈdiː.dɒs/ *DEE-doss*), the incoming traffic flooding the victim originates from many different sources.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] More sophisticated strategies are required to mitigate this type of attack; simply attempting to block a single source is insufficient.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A DDoS attack is analogous to a group of people crowding the entry door of a shop, making it hard for legitimate customers to enter, thus disrupting trade and losing the business money.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Criminal perpetrators of DDoS attacks often target sites or services hosted on high-profile web servers such as banks or credit card payment gateways.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Revenge and blackmail, as well as hacktivism, can motivate these attacks.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Panix, the third-oldest Internet service provider (ISP) in the world, was the target of what is thought to be the first DoS attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] On September 6, 1996, Panix was subject to a SYN flood attack, which brought down its services for several days while hardware vendors, notably Cisco, figured out a proper defense.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The release of sample code during the event led to the online attack of Sprint, EarthLink, E-Trade, and other major corporations in the year to follow.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In February 2020, Amazon Web Services experienced an attack with a peak volume of 2.3 Tb/s.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In July 2021, Cloudflare boasted of protecting its client from a DDoS attack from a global Mirai botnet that was up to 17.2 million requests per second.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Russian DDoS prevention provider Yandex said it blocked an HTTP pipelining DDoS attack on Sept.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] 2021 that originated from unpatched Mikrotik networking gear.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In the first half of 2022, the Russian invasion of Ukraine significantly shaped the cyberthreat landscape, with an increase in cyberattacks attributed to both state-sponsored actors and global hacktivist activities.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The most notable event was a DDoS attack in February, the largest Ukraine has encountered, disrupting government and financial sector services.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This wave of cyber aggression extended to Western allies like the UK, the US, and Germany.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Particularly, the UK's financial sector saw an increase in DDoS attacks from nation-state actors and hacktivists, aimed at undermining Ukraine's allies.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In February 2023, Cloudflare faced a 71 million requests per second attack which they claimed was the largest HTTP DDoS attack at the time.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] HTTP DDoS attacks are measured by HTTP requests per second instead of packets per second or bits per second.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] On July 10, 2023, the fanfiction platform Archive of Our Own (AO3) faced DDoS attacks, disrupting services.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Anonymous Sudan, claiming the attack for religious and political reasons, was viewed skeptically by AO3 and experts.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Flashpoint, a threat intelligence vendor, noted the group's past activities but doubted their stated motives.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] AO3, supported by the non-profit Organization for Transformative Works (OTW) and reliant on donations, is unlikely to meet the $30,000 Bitcoin ransom.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In August 2023, the group of hacktivists NoName057 targeted several Italian financial institutions, through the execution of slow DoS attacks.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] On 14 January 2024, they executed a DDoS attack on Swiss federal websites, prompted by President Zelensky's attendance at the Davos World Economic Forum.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Switzerland's National Cyber Security Centre quickly mitigated the attack, ensuring core federal services remained secure, despite temporary accessibility issues on some websites.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2023, exploitation of a new vulnerability in the HTTP/2 protocol resulted in the record for largest HTTP DDoS attack being broken twice, once with a 201 million requests per second attack observed by Cloudflare, and again with a 398 million requests per second attack observed by Google.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In August 2024, Global Secure Layer observed and reported on a record-breaking packet DDoS at 3.15 billion packets per second, which targeted an undisclosed number of unofficial Minecraft game servers.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2024, the Internet Archive faced two severe DDoS attacks that brought the site completely offline, immediately following a previous attack that leaked records of over 31 million of the site's users.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The hacktivist group SN_Blackmeta claimed the DDoS attack as retribution for American involvement in the Gaza war, despite the Internet Archive being unaffiliated with the United States government; however, their link with the preceding data leak remains unclear.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Cloudflare claims to have recorded and successfully autonomously blocked a 40-second DDoS attack on 23 September 2025, that reached a peak volume of 22.2 Tbit/s, which would be the largest DDoS attack to date.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Cloudflare has stated that over 404,000 source IPs were used to target one IP address, and that the source IPs were not spoofed.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] According to Cloudflare, this came after several other large-scale DDoS attacks, each consecutively beating the previous record, including a 7.3 Tbit/s attack in May 2025 and an 11.5 Tbit/s attack on 1 September 2025.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Denial-of-service attacks are characterized by an explicit attempt by attackers to prevent legitimate use of a service.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] There are two general forms of DoS attacks: those that crash services and those that flood services.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The most serious attacks are distributed.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack occurs when multiple systems flood the bandwidth or resources of a targeted system, usually one or more web servers.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A DDoS attack uses more than one unique IP address or machines, often from thousands of hosts infected with malware.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial of service attack typically involves more than around 3–5 nodes on different networks; fewer nodes may qualify as a DoS attack but is not a DDoS attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Most of the time, attackers operate from an endpoint that is not their intended target, for example using another user's machine to attack a server.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] By using another unsuspecting endpoint if it becomes compromised they can then move onto another workstation within the enterprise network.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] However, even faking lots of users and executing a DoS attack, a single attacker with few computers is still very limited in the amount of traffic they can generate.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] If the attacks are from multiple sources, it can be difficult for the host to identify and stop them.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The scale of DDoS attacks has continued to rise over recent years, by 2016 exceeding a terabit per second.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Some common examples of DDoS attacks are UDP flooding, SYN flooding and DNS amplification.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A **yo-yo attack** is a specific type of DoS/DDoS aimed at cloud-hosted applications which use autoscaling.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] During the attack, an attacker repeatedly changes between sending a lot of traffic (which causes a scale-up) and stopping the burst (causing a scale-down as a result).
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] An **application layer DDoS attack** (sometimes referred to as **layer 7 DDoS attack**) is a form of DDoS attack where attackers target application-layer processes.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The attack over-exercises specific functions or features of a website with the intention to disable those functions or features.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This application-layer attack is different from an entire network attack, and is often used against financial institutions to distract IT and security personnel from security breaches.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In 2013, application-layer DDoS attacks represented 20% of all DDoS attacks.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] According to research by Akamai Technologies, there have been "51 percent more application layer attacks" from Q4 2013 to Q4 2014 and "16 percent more" from Q3 2014 to Q4 2014.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In November 2017; Junade Ali, an engineer at Cloudflare noted that whilst network-level attacks continue to be of high capacity, they were occurring less frequently.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Ali further noted that although network-level attacks were becoming less frequent, data from Cloudflare demonstrated that application-layer attacks were still showing no sign of slowing down.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The simplest DoS attack relies primarily on brute force, flooding the target with an overwhelming flux of packets, oversaturating its connection bandwidth or depleting the target's system resources.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Bandwidth-saturating floods rely on the attacker's ability to generate the overwhelming flux of packets.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A common way of achieving this today is via distributed denial-of-service, employing a botnet.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] An application layer DDoS attack is done mainly for specific targeted purposes, including disrupting transactions and access to databases.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] It requires fewer resources than network layer attacks but often accompanies them.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] An attack may be disguised to look like legitimate traffic, except it targets specific application packets or functions.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The attack on the application layer can disrupt services such as the retrieval of information or search functions on a website.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] An **advanced persistent DoS** (APDoS) is associated with an advanced persistent threat and requires specialized DDoS mitigation.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] These attacks can persist for weeks; the longest continuous period noted so far lasted 38 days.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This attack involved approximately 50+ petabits (50,000+ terabits) of malicious traffic.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers in this scenario may tactically switch between several targets to create a diversion to evade defensive DDoS countermeasures but all the while eventually concentrating the main thrust of the attack onto a single victim.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In this scenario, attackers with continuous access to several very powerful network resources are capable of sustaining a prolonged campaign generating enormous levels of unamplified DDoS traffic.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Some vendors provide so-called *booter* or *stresser* services, which have simple web-based front ends, and accept payment over the web.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Marketed and promoted as stress-testing tools, they can be used to perform unauthorized denial-of-service attacks, and allow technically unsophisticated attackers access to sophisticated attack tools.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Usually powered by a botnet, the traffic produced by a consumer stresser can range anywhere from 5-50 Gbit/s, which can, in most cases, deny the average home user internet access.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A Markov-modulated denial-of-service attack occurs when the attacker disrupts control packets using a hidden Markov model.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A setting in which Markov-model-based attacks are prevalent is online gaming as the disruption of the control packet undermines gameplay and system functionality.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In cases such as MyDoom and Slowloris, the tools are embedded in malware and launch their attacks without the knowledge of the system owner.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Stacheldraht is a classic example of a DDoS tool.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] It uses a layered structure where the attacker uses a client program to connect to handlers which are compromised systems that issue commands to the zombie agents which in turn facilitate the DDoS attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Agents are compromised via the handlers by the attacker using automated routines to exploit vulnerabilities in programs that accept remote connections running on the targeted remote hosts.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Each handler can control up to a thousand agents.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In other cases a machine may become part of a DDoS attack with the owner's consent, for example, in Operation Payback organized by the group Anonymous.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The Low Orbit Ion Cannon has typically been used in this way.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Along with High Orbit Ion Cannon a wide variety of DDoS tools are available today, including paid and free versions, with different features available.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] There is an underground market for these in hacker-related forums and IRC channels.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Application-layer attacks employ DoS-causing exploits and can cause server-running software to fill the disk space or consume all available memory or CPU time.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Attacks may use specific packet types or connection requests to saturate finite resources by, for example, occupying the maximum number of open connections or filling the victim's disk space with logs.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] An attacker with shell-level access to a victim's computer may slow it until it is unusable or crash it by using a fork bomb.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Another kind of application-level DoS attack is XDoS (or XML DoS) which can be controlled by modern web application firewalls (WAFs).
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] All attacks belonging to the category of *timeout exploiting*.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Slow DoS attacks implement an application-layer attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Examples of threats are Slowloris, establishing pending connections with the victim, or SlowDroid, an attack running on mobile devices.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Another target of DDoS attacks may be to produce added costs for the application operator, when the latter uses resources based on cloud computing.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In this case, normally application-used resources are tied to a needed quality of service (QoS) level (e.g. responses should be less than 200 ms) and this rule is usually linked to automated software (e.g.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Amazon CloudWatch) to raise more virtual resources from the provider to meet the defined QoS levels for the increased requests.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The main incentive behind such attacks may be to drive the application owner to raise the elasticity levels to handle the increased application traffic, to cause financial losses, or force them to become less competitive.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A *banana attack* is another particular type of DoS.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] It involves redirecting outgoing messages from the client back onto the client, preventing outside access, as well as flooding the client with the sent packets.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Pulsing zombies are compromised computers that are directed to launch intermittent and short-lived flooding of victim websites with the intent of merely slowing it rather than crashing it.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This type of attack, referred to as *degradation-of-service*, can be more difficult to detect and can disrupt and hamper connection to websites for prolonged periods of time, potentially causing more overall disruption than a denial-of-service attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Exposure of degradation-of-service attacks is complicated further by the matter of discerning whether the server is really being attacked or is experiencing higher than normal legitimate traffic loads.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] If an attacker mounts an attack from a single host, it would be classified as a DoS attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Any attack against availability would be classed as a denial-of-service attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] On the other hand, if an attacker uses many systems to simultaneously launch attacks against a remote host, this would be classified as a DDoS attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Malware can carry DDoS attack mechanisms; one of the better-known examples of this was MyDoom.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Its DoS mechanism was triggered on a specific date and time.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This type of DDoS involved hardcoding the target IP address before releasing the malware and no further interaction was necessary to launch the attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A system may also be compromised with a trojan containing a zombie agent.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers can also break into systems using automated tools that exploit flaws in programs that listen for connections from remote hosts.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This scenario primarily concerns systems acting as servers on the web.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] It uses a layered structure where the attacker uses a client program to connect to handlers, which are compromised systems that issue commands to the zombie agents, which in turn facilitate the DDoS attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Agents are compromised via the handlers by the attacker.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In some cases a machine may become part of a DDoS attack with the owner's consent, for example, in Operation Payback, organized by the group Anonymous.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] These attacks can use different types of internet packets such as TCP, UDP, ICMP, etc.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] These collections of compromised systems are known as botnets.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] DDoS tools like Stacheldraht still use classic DoS attack methods centered on IP spoofing and amplification like smurf attacks and fraggle attacks (types of bandwidth consumption attacks).
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] SYN floods (a resource starvation attack) may also be used.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Newer tools can use DNS servers for DoS purposes.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Unlike MyDoom's DDoS mechanism, botnets can be turned against any IP address.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Script kiddies use them to deny the availability of well known websites to legitimate users.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] More sophisticated attackers use DDoS tools for the purposes of extortion – including against their business rivals.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] It has been reported that there are new attacks from internet of things (IoT) devices that have been involved in denial of service attacks.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] One such attack peaked at around 20,000 requests per second; it came from around 900 CCTV cameras.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] UK's GCHQ has tools built for DDoS, named PREDATORS FACE and ROLLING THUNDER.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Simple attacks such as SYN floods may appear with a wide range of source IP addresses, giving the appearance of a distributed DoS.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] These flood attacks do not require completion of the TCP three-way handshake and attempt to exhaust the destination SYN queue or the server bandwidth.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Because the source IP addresses can be trivially spoofed, an attack could come from a limited set of sources, or may even originate from a single host.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Stack enhancements such as SYN cookies may be effective mitigation against SYN queue flooding but do not address bandwidth exhaustion.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In 2022, TCP attacks were the leading method in DDoS incidents, accounting for 63% of all DDoS activity.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This includes tactics like TCP SYN, TCP ACK, and TCP floods.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] With TCP being the most widespread networking protocol, its attacks are expected to remain prevalent in the DDoS threat scene.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In 2015, DDoS botnets such as DD4BC grew in prominence, taking aim at financial institutions.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Cyber-extortionists typically begin with a low-level attack and a warning that a larger attack will be carried out if a ransom is not paid in bitcoin.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Security experts recommend targeted websites to not pay the ransom.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The attackers tend to get into an extended extortion scheme once they recognize that the target is ready to pay.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] First discovered in 2009, the HTTP slow POST attack sends a complete, legitimate HTTP POST header, which includes a *Content-Length* field to specify the size of the message body to follow.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] However, the attacker then proceeds to send the actual message body at an extremely slow rate (e.g.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Due to the entire message being correct and complete, the target server will attempt to obey the *Content-Length* field in the header and wait for the entire body of the message to be transmitted, which can take a very long time.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker establishes hundreds or even thousands of such connections until all resources for incoming connections on the victim server are exhausted, making any further connections impossible until all data has been sent.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] It is notable that unlike many other DoS or DDoS attacks, which try to subdue the server by overloading its network or CPU, an HTTP slow POST attack targets the *logical* resources of the victim, which means the victim would still have enough network bandwidth and processing power to operate.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Combined with the fact that the Apache HTTP Server will, by default, accept requests up to 2GB in size, this attack can be particularly powerful.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] HTTP slow POST attacks are difficult to differentiate from legitimate connections and are therefore able to bypass some protection systems.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] OWASP, an open source web application security project, released a tool to test the security of servers against this type of attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A Challenge Collapsar (CC) attack is an attack where standard HTTP requests are sent to a targeted web server frequently.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The Uniform Resource Identifiers (URIs) in the requests require complicated time-consuming algorithms or database operations which may exhaust the resources of the targeted web server.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In 2004, a Chinese hacker nicknamed KiKi invented a hacking tool to send these kinds of requests to attack a NSFOCUS firewall named Collapsar, and thus the hacking tool was known as Challenge Collapsar, or *CC* for short.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Consequently, this type of attack got the name *CC attack*.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A smurf attack relies on misconfigured network devices that allow packets to be sent to all computer hosts on a particular network via the broadcast address of the network, rather than a specific machine.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker will send large numbers of IP packets with the source address faked to appear to be the address of the victim.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Most devices on a network will, by default, respond to this by sending a reply to the source IP address.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] If the number of machines on the network that receive and respond to these packets is very large, the victim's computer will be flooded with traffic.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This overloads the victim's computer and can even make it unusable during such an attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Ping flood is based on sending the victim an overwhelming number of ping packets, usually using the *ping* command from Unix-like hosts.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] It is very simple to launch, the primary requirement being access to greater bandwidth than the victim.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Ping of death is based on sending the victim a malformed ping packet, which will lead to a system crash on a vulnerable system.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The BlackNurse attack is an example of an attack taking advantage of the required Destination Port Unreachable ICMP packets.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A specific example of a nuke attack that gained some prominence is the WinNuke, which exploited the vulnerability in the NetBIOS handler in Windows 95.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A string of out-of-band data was sent to TCP port 139 of the victim's machine, causing it to lock up and display a Blue Screen of Death.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Attackers have found a way to exploit a number of bugs in peer-to-peer servers to initiate DDoS attacks.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The most aggressive of these peer-to-peer-DDoS attacks exploits the DC++ file sharing network.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] With peer-to-peer attacks there is no botnet and the attacker does not have to communicate with the clients it subverts.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Instead, the attacker acts as a *puppet master*, instructing clients of large peer-to-peer file sharing hubs to disconnect from their peer-to-peer network and to connect to the victim's website instead.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Permanent denial-of-service (PDoS), also known loosely as phlashing, is an attack that damages a system so badly that it requires replacement or reinstallation of hardware.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Unlike the distributed denial-of-service attack, a PDoS attack exploits security flaws which allow remote administration on the management interfaces of the victim's hardware, such as routers, printers, or other networking hardware.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The PDoS is a pure hardware-targeted attack that can be much faster and requires fewer resources than using a botnet in a DDoS attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Because of these features, and the potential and high probability of security exploits on network-enabled embedded devices, this technique has come to the attention of numerous hacking communities.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] BrickerBot, a piece of malware that targeted IoT devices, used PDoS attacks to disable its targets.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] PhlashDance is a tool created by Rich Smith (an employee of Hewlett-Packard's Systems Security Lab) used to detect and demonstrate PDoS vulnerabilities at the 2008 EUSecWest Applied Security Conference in London, UK.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A distributed denial-of-service attack may involve sending forged requests of some type to a very large number of computers that will reply to the requests.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Using Internet Protocol address spoofing, the source address is set to that of the targeted victim, which means all the replies will go to (and flood) the target.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This reflected attack form is sometimes called a distributed reflective denial-of-service (DRDoS) attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] ICMP echo request attacks (Smurf attacks) can be considered one form of reflected attack, as the flooding hosts send Echo Requests to the broadcast addresses of mis-configured networks, thereby enticing hosts to send Echo Reply packets to the victim.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Some early DDoS programs implemented a distributed form of this attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Amplification attacks are used to magnify the bandwidth that is sent to a victim.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Many services can be exploited to act as reflectors, some harder to block than others.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] DNS amplification attacks involves an attacker sending a DNS name lookup request to one or more public DNS servers, spoofing the source IP address of the targeted victim.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The attacker tries to request as much information as possible, thus amplifying the DNS response that is sent to the targeted victim.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Since the size of the request is significantly smaller than the response, the attacker is easily able to increase the amount of traffic directed at the target.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) and Network Time Protocol (NTP) can also be exploited as reflectors in an amplification attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] An example of an amplified DDoS attack through the NTP is through a command called monlist, which sends the details of the last 600 hosts that have requested the time from the NTP server back to the requester.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A small request to this time server can be sent using a spoofed source IP address of some victim, which results in a response 556.9 times the size of the request being sent to the victim.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This becomes amplified when using botnets that all send requests with the same spoofed IP source, which will result in a massive amount of data being sent back to the victim.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] It is very difficult to defend against these types of attacks because the response data is coming from legitimate servers.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] These attack requests are also sent through UDP, which does not require a connection to the server.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This means that the source IP is not verified when a request is received by the server.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] To bring awareness of these vulnerabilities, campaigns have been started that are dedicated to finding amplification vectors which have led to people fixing their resolvers or having the resolvers shut down completely.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The Mirai botnet works by using a computer worm to infect hundreds of thousands of IoT devices across the internet.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The worm propagates through networks and systems taking control of poorly protected IoT devices such as thermostats, Wi-Fi-enabled clocks, and washing machines.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The owner or user will usually have no immediate indication of when the device becomes infected.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The IoT device itself is not the direct target of the attack; it is used as part of a larger attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Once the hacker has enslaved the desired number of devices, they instruct the devices to try to contact an ISP.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In October 2016, a Mirai botnet attacked Dyn which is the ISP for sites such as Twitter, Netflix, etc.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] As soon as this occurred, these websites were all unreachable for several hours.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] RUDY attack targets web applications by starvation of available sessions on the web server.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Much like Slowloris, RUDY keeps sessions at a halt using never-ending POST transmissions and sending an arbitrarily large content-length header value.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Manipulating maximum segment size and selective acknowledgement (SACK) may be used by a remote peer to cause a denial of service by an integer overflow in the Linux kernel, potentially causing a kernel panic.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The shrew attack is a denial-of-service attack on the Transmission Control Protocol where the attacker employs man-in-the-middle techniques.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] It exploits a weakness in TCP's re-transmission timeout mechanism, using short synchronized bursts of traffic to disrupt TCP connections on the same link.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A slow read attack sends legitimate application layer requests, but reads responses very slowly, keeping connections open longer hoping to exhaust the server's connection pool.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The slow read is achieved by advertising a very small number for the TCP Receive Window size, and at the same time emptying clients' TCP receive buffer slowly, which causes a very low data flow rate.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A sophisticated low-bandwidth DDoS attack is a form of DoS that uses less traffic and increases its effectiveness by aiming at a weak point in the victim's system design, i.e., the attacker sends traffic consisting of complicated requests to the system.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Essentially, a sophisticated DDoS attack is lower in cost due to its use of less traffic, is smaller in size making it more difficult to identify, and it can hurt systems which are protected by flow control mechanisms.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A SYN flood occurs when a host sends a flood of TCP/SYN packets, often with a forged sender address.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Each of these packets is handled like a connection request, causing the server to spawn a half-open connection, send back a TCP/SYN-ACK packet, and wait for a packet in response from the sender address.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] However, because the sender's address is forged, the response never comes.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] These half-open connections exhaust the available connections the server can make, keeping it from responding to legitimate requests until after the attack ends.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A **teardrop attack** involves sending mangled IP fragments with overlapping, oversized payloads to the target machine.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This can crash various operating systems because of a bug in their TCP/IP fragmentation re-assembly code.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Windows 3.1x, Windows 95 and Windows NT operating systems, as well as versions of Linux before versions 2.0.32 and 2.1.63 are vulnerable to this attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] One of the fields in an IP header is the *fragment offset* field, indicating the starting position, or offset, of the data contained in a fragmented packet relative to the data in the original packet.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] If the sum of the offset and size of one fragmented packet differs from that of the next fragmented packet, the packets overlap.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] When this happens, a server vulnerable to teardrop attacks is unable to reassemble the packets resulting in a denial-of-service condition.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Voice over IP has made abusive origination of large numbers of telephone voice calls inexpensive and easily automated while permitting call origins to be misrepresented through caller ID spoofing.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] TDoS can exist even without Internet telephony.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In the 2002 New Hampshire Senate election phone jamming scandal, telemarketers were used to flood political opponents with spurious calls to jam phone banks on election day.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Widespread publication of a number can also flood it with enough calls to render it unusable, as happened by accident in 1981 with multiple +1-area code-867-5309 subscribers inundated by hundreds of calls daily in response to the song "867-5309/Jenny".
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] TDoS differs from other telephone harassment (such as prank calls and obscene phone calls) by the number of calls originated.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] By occupying lines continuously with repeated automated calls, the victim is prevented from making or receiving both routine and emergency telephone calls.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Related exploits include SMS flooding attacks and black fax or continuous fax transmission by using a loop of paper at the sender.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] It takes more router resources to drop a packet with a TTL value of 1 or less than it does to forward a packet with a higher TTL value.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] When a packet is dropped due to TTL expiry, the router CPU must generate and send an ICMP time exceeded response.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Generating many of these responses can overload the router's CPU.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A UPnP attack uses an existing vulnerability in Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) protocol to get past network security and flood a target's network and servers.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The attack is based on a DNS amplification technique, but the attack mechanism is a UPnP router that forwards requests from one outer source to another.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The UPnP router returns the data on an unexpected UDP port from a bogus IP address, making it harder to take simple action to shut down the traffic flood.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] According to the Imperva researchers, the most effective way to stop this attack is for companies to lock down UPnP routers.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In 2014, it was discovered that Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) was being used in DDoS attacks known as an SSDP reflection attac*k* *with amplification*.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Many devices, including some residential routers, have a vulnerability in the UPnP software that allows an attacker to get replies from UDP port 1900 to a destination address of their choice.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] With a botnet of thousands of devices, the attackers can generate sufficient packet rates and occupy bandwidth to saturate links, causing the denial of service.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Because of this weakness, the network company Cloudflare has described SSDP as the "Stupidly Simple DDoS Protocol".
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Defensive responses to denial-of-service attacks typically involve the use of a combination of attack detection, traffic classification and response tools, aiming to block traffic the tools identify as illegitimate and allow traffic that they identify as legitimate.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A list of response tools include the following.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] All traffic destined to the victim is diverted to pass through a *cleaning center* or a *scrubbing center* via various methods such as: changing the victim IP address in the DNS system, tunneling methods (GRE/VRF, MPLS, SDN), proxies, digital cross connects, or even direct circuits.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The cleaning center separates *bad* traffic (DDoS and also other common internet attacks) and only passes good legitimate traffic to the victim server.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The victim needs central connectivity to the Internet to use this kind of service unless they happen to be located within the same facility as the cleaning center.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] DDoS attacks can overwhelm any type of hardware firewall, and passing malicious traffic through large and mature networks becomes more and more effective and economically sustainable against DDoS.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Application front-end hardware is intelligent hardware placed on the network before traffic reaches the servers.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] It can be used on networks in conjunction with routers and switches and as part of bandwidth management.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Application front-end hardware analyzes data packets as they enter the network, and identifies and drops dangerous or suspicious flows.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Approaches to detection of DDoS attacks against cloud-based applications may be based on an application layer analysis, indicating whether incoming bulk traffic is legitimate.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] These approaches mainly rely on an identified path of value inside the application and monitor the progress of requests on this path, through markers called *key completion indicators*.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In essence, these techniques are statistical methods of assessing the behavior of incoming requests to detect if something unusual or abnormal is going on.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] An analogy is to a brick-and-mortar department store where customers spend, on average, a known percentage of their time on different activities such as picking up items and examining them, putting them back, filling a basket, waiting to pay, paying, and leaving.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] If a mob of customers arrived in the store and spent all their time picking up items and putting them back, but never made any purchases, this could be flagged as unusual behavior.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] With blackhole routing, all the traffic to the attacked DNS or IP address is sent to a *black hole* (null interface or a non-existent server).
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] To be more efficient and avoid affecting network connectivity, it can be managed by the ISP.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A DNS sinkhole routes traffic to a valid IP address which analyzes traffic and rejects bad packets.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Sinkholing may not be efficient for severe attacks.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Intrusion prevention systems (IPS) are effective if the attacks have signatures associated with them.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] However, the trend among attacks is to have legitimate content but bad intent.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Intrusion-prevention systems that work on content recognition cannot block behavior-based DoS attacks.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] An ASIC based IPS may detect and block denial-of-service attacks because they have the processing power and the granularity to analyze the attacks and act like a circuit breaker in an automated way.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] More focused on the problem than IPS, a DoS defense system (DDS) can block connection-based DoS attacks and those with legitimate content but bad intent.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A DDS can also address both protocol attacks (such as teardrop and ping of death) and rate-based attacks (such as ICMP floods and SYN floods).
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] DDS has a purpose-built system that can easily identify and obstruct denial of service attacks at a greater speed than a software-based system.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In the case of a simple attack, a firewall can be adjusted to deny all incoming traffic from the attackers, based on protocols, ports, or the originating IP addresses.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] More complex attacks will however be hard to block with simple rules: for example, if there is an ongoing attack on port 80 (web service), it is not possible to drop all incoming traffic on this port because doing so will prevent the server from receiving and serving legitimate traffic.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Additionally, firewalls may be too deep in the network hierarchy, with routers being adversely affected before the traffic gets to the firewall.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Also, many security tools still do not support IPv6 or may not be configured properly, so the firewalls may be bypassed during the attacks.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Similar to switches, routers have some rate-limiting and ACL capabilities.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Most routers can be easily overwhelmed under a DoS attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Nokia SR-OS using FP4 or FP5 processors offers DDoS protection.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Nokia SR-OS also uses big data analytics-based Nokia Deepfield Defender for DDoS protection.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Cisco IOS has optional features that can reduce the impact of flooding.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Most switches have some rate-limiting and ACL capability.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Some switches provide automatic or system-wide rate limiting, traffic shaping, delayed binding (TCP splicing), deep packet inspection and bogon filtering (bogus IP filtering) to detect and remediate DoS attacks through automatic rate filtering and WAN Link failover and balancing.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] These schemes will work as long as the DoS attacks can be prevented by using them.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] For example, SYN flood can be prevented using delayed binding or TCP splicing.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Similarly, content-based DoS may be prevented using deep packet inspection.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Attacks using Martian packets can be prevented using bogon filtering.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Automatic rate filtering can work as long as set rate thresholds have been set correctly.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] WAN-link failover will work as long as both links have a DoS prevention mechanism.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Threats may be associated with specific TCP or UDP port numbers.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Blocking these ports at the firewall can mitigate an attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] For example, in an SSDP reflection attack, the key mitigation is to block incoming UDP traffic on port 1900.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Blocking specific Time to live (TTL) values based on the network path length can be a viable option for blocking spoofed attacks.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] An unintentional denial-of-service can occur when a system ends up denied, not due to a deliberate attack by a single individual or group of individuals, but simply due to a sudden enormous spike in popularity.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This can happen when an extremely popular website posts a prominent link to a second, less well-prepared site, for example, as part of a news story.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The result is that a significant proportion of the primary site's regular users – potentially hundreds of thousands of people – click that link in the space of a few hours, having the same effect on the target website as a DDoS attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] A VIPDoS is the same, but specifically when the link was posted by a celebrity.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] When Michael Jackson died in 2009, websites such as Google and Twitter slowed down or even crashed.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Many sites' servers thought the requests were from a virus or spyware trying to cause a denial-of-service attack, warning users that their queries looked like "automated requests from a computer virus or spyware application".
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] News sites and link sites – sites whose primary function is to provide links to interesting content elsewhere on the Internet – are most likely to cause this phenomenon.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The canonical example is the Slashdot effect when receiving traffic from Slashdot.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] It is also known as "the Reddit hug of death" and "the Digg effect".
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Similar unintentional denial-of-service can also occur via other media, e.g. when a URL is mentioned on television.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In March 2014, after Malaysia Airlines Flight 370 went missing, DigitalGlobe launched a crowdsourcing service on which users could help search for the missing jet in satellite images.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The response overwhelmed the company's servers.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] An unintentional denial-of-service may also result from a prescheduled event created by the website itself, as was the case of the Census in Australia in 2016.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Legal action has been taken in at least one such case.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In 2006, Universal Tube & Rollform Equipment Corporation sued YouTube: massive numbers of would-be YouTube.com users accidentally typed the tube company's URL, utube.com.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] As a result, the tube company ended up having to spend large amounts of money on upgrading its bandwidth.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Routers have also been known to create unintentional DoS attacks, as both D-Link and Netgear routers have overloaded NTP servers by flooding them without respecting the restrictions of client types or geographical limitations.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In computer network security, backscatter is a side-effect of a spoofed denial-of-service attack.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In this kind of attack, the attacker spoofs the source address in IP packets sent to the victim.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In general, the victim machine cannot distinguish between the spoofed packets and legitimate packets, so the victim responds to the spoofed packets as it normally would.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] These response packets are known as backscatter.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] If the attacker is spoofing source addresses randomly, the backscatter response packets from the victim will be sent back to random destinations.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] This effect can be used by network telescopes as indirect evidence of such attacks.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The term *backscatter analysis* refers to observing backscatter packets arriving at a statistically significant portion of the IP address space to determine the characteristics of DoS attacks and victims.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Many jurisdictions have laws under which denial-of-service attacks are illegal.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] UNCTAD highlights that 156 countries, or 80% globally, have enacted cybercrime laws to combat its widespread impact.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Adoption rates vary by region, with Europe at a 91% rate, and Africa at 72%.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In the US, denial-of-service attacks may be considered a federal crime under the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act with penalties that include years of imprisonment.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The Computer Crime and Intellectual Property Section of the US Department of Justice handles cases of DoS and DDoS.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In one example, in July 2019, Austin Thompson, aka DerpTrolling, was sentenced to 27 months in prison and $95,000 in restitution by a federal court for conducting multiple DDoS attacks on major video gaming companies, disrupting their systems for hours to days.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In European countries, committing criminal denial-of-service attacks may, as a minimum, lead to arrest.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] The United Kingdom is unusual in that it specifically outlawed denial-of-service attacks and set a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison with the Police and Justice Act 2006, which amended Section 3 of the Computer Misuse Act 1990.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] In January 2019, Europol announced that "actions are currently underway worldwide to track down the users" of Webstresser.org, a former DDoS marketplace that was shut down in April 2018 as part of Operation PowerOFF.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] Europol said UK police were conducting a number of "live operations" targeting over 250 users of Webstresser and other DDoS services.
[src:graphql-security/denial-of-service-attack] On January 7, 2013, Anonymous posted a petition on the whitehouse.gov site asking that DDoS be recognized as a legal form of protest similar to the Occupy movement, the claim being that the similarity in the purpose of both is same.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] GraphQL is an open source query language originally developed by Facebook that can be used to build APIs as an alternative to REST and SOAP.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] It has gained popularity since its inception in 2012 because of the native flexibility it offers to those building and calling the API.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] There are GraphQL servers and clients implemented in various languages.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Many companies use GraphQL including GitHub, Credit Karma, Intuit, and PayPal.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Adding strict input validation can help prevent against injection and DoS.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] The main design for GraphQL is that the user supplies one or more identifiers and the backend has a number of data fetchers making HTTP, DB, or other calls using the given identifiers.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This means that user input will be included in HTTP requests, DB queries, or other requests/calls which provides opportunity for injection that could lead to various injection attacks or DoS.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] See the OWASP Cheat Sheets on Input Validation and general injection prevention for full details to best perform input validation and prevent injection.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Validate all incoming data to only allow valid values (i.e. allowlist).
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] When using user input, even if sanitized and/or validated, it should not be used for certain purposes that would give a user control over data flow.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] For example, do not make an HTTP/resource request to a host that the user supplies (unless there is an absolute business need).
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] DoS is an attack against the availability and stability of the API that can make it slow, unresponsive, or completely unavailable.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This CS details several methods to limit the possibility of a DoS attack at the application level and other layers of the tech stack.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] There is also a CS dedicated to the topic of DoS.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] In GraphQL each query has a depth (*e.g.* nested objects) and each object requested in a query can have an amount specified (*e.g.* 99999999 of an object).
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] By default these can both be unlimited which may lead to a DoS.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] You should set limits on depth and amount to prevent DoS, but this usually requires a small custom implementation as it is not natively supported by GraphQL.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] See this and this page for more information about these attacks and how to add depth and amount limiting.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Adding pagination can also help performance.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] APIs using graphql-java can utilize the built-in MaxQueryDepthInstrumentation for depth limiting.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] APIs using JavaScript can use graphql-depth-limit to implement depth limiting and graphql-input-number to implement amount limiting.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Adding timeouts can be a simple way to limit how many resources any single request can consume.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] But timeouts are not always effective since they may not activate until a malicious query has already consumed excessive resources.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Timeout requirements will differ by API and data fetching mechanism; there isn't one timeout value that will work across the board.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] At the application level, timeouts can be added for queries and resolver functions.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This option is usually more effective since the query/resolution can be stopped once the timeout is reached.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] GraphQL does not natively support query timeouts so custom code is required.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] See this blog post for more about using timeouts with GraphQL or the two examples below.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Another option to add a timeout that is usually easier is adding a timeout on an HTTP server (Apache/httpd, nginx), reverse proxy, or load balancer.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] However, infrastructure timeouts are often inaccurate and can be bypassed more easily than application-level ones.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Query cost analysis involves assigning costs to the resolution of fields or types in incoming queries so that the server can reject queries that cost too much to run or will consume too many resources.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This is not easy to implement and may not always be necessary but it is the most thorough approach to preventing DoS.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] See "Query Cost Analysis" in this blog post for more details on implementing this control.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] APIs using graphql-java can utilize the built-in MaxQueryComplexityInstrumentationto to enforce max query complexity.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] APIs using JavaScript can utilize graphql-cost-analysis or graphql-validation-complexity to enforce max query cost.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Enforcing rate limiting on a per IP or user (for anonymous and unauthorized access) basis can help limit a single user's ability to spam requests to the service and impact performance.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Ideally this can be done with a WAF, API gateway, or web server (Nginx, Apache/HTTPD) to reduce the effort of adding rate limiting.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Or you could get somewhat complex with throttling and implement it in your code (non-trivial).
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] See "Throttling" here for more about GraphQL-specific rate limiting.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] To increase efficiency of a GraphQL API and reduce its resource consumption, the batching and caching technique can be used to prevent making duplicate requests for pieces of data within a small time frame.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Facebook's DataLoader tool is one way to implement this.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Not properly limiting the amount of resources your API can use (*e.g.* CPU or memory), may compromise your API responsiveness and availability, leaving it vulnerable to DoS attacks.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Some limiting can be done at the operating system level.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] On Linux, a combination of Control Groups(cgroups), User Limits (ulimits), and Linux Containers (LXC) can be used.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] However, containerization platforms tend to make this task much easier.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] See the resource limiting section in the Docker Security Cheat Sheet for how to prevent DoS when using containers.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] It's commonplace for GraphQL requests to include one or more direct IDs of objects in order to fetch or modify them.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] For example, a request for a certain picture may include the ID that is actually the primary key in the database for that picture.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] As with any request, the server must verify that the caller has access to the object they are requesting.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] But sometimes developers make the mistake of assuming that possession of the object's ID means the caller should have access.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Failure to verify the requester's access in this case is called Broken Object Level Authentication, also known as IDOR.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] It's possible for a GraphQL API to support access to objects using their ID even if that is not intended.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Sometimes there are `node` or `nodes` or both fields in a query object, and these can be used to access objects directly by `ID`.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] You can check whether your schema has these fields by running this on the command-line (assuming that `schema.json` contains your GraphQL schema): `cat schema.json | jq ".data.__schema.types[] | select(.name==\"Query\") | .fields[] | .name" | grep node`.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Removing these fields from the schema should disable the functionality, but you should always apply proper authorization checks to verify the caller has access to the object they are requesting.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] As part of a GraphQL API there will be various data fields that can be returned.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] One thing to consider is if you want different levels of access around these fields.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] For example, you may only want certain consumers to be able to fetch certain data fields rather than allowing all consumers to be able to retrieve all available fields.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This can be done by adding a check in the code to ensure that the requester should be able to read a field they are trying to fetch.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] GraphQL supports mutation, or manipulation of data, in addition to its most common use case of data fetching.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] If an API implements/allows mutation then there may need to be access controls put in place to restrict which consumers, if any, can modify data through the API.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Setups that require mutation access control would include APIs where only read access is intended for requesters or where only certain parties should be able to modify certain fields.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] GraphQL supports batching requests, also known as query batching.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This lets callers to either batch multiple queries or batch requests for multiple object instances in a single network call, which allows for what is called a batching attack.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This is a form of brute force attack, specific to GraphQL, that usually allows for faster and less detectable exploits.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] In this case it could be used to enumerate every possible `droid` object that is stored on the server in very few network requests as opposed to a standard REST API where the requester would need to submit a different network request for every different `droid` ID they want to request.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] In order to mitigate this type of attack you should put limits on incoming requests at the code level so that they can be applied per request.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] One option is to create a code-level rate limit on how many objects that callers can request.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This means the backend would track how many different object instances the caller has requested, so that they will be blocked after requesting too many objects even if they batch the object requests in a single network call.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This replicates a network-level rate limit that a WAF or other tool would do.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Another option is to prevent batching for sensitive objects that you don't want to be brute forced, such as usernames, emails, passwords, OTPs, session tokens, etc.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This way an attacker is forced to attack the API like a REST API and make a different network call per object instance.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This is not supported natively so it will require a custom solution.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] However once this control is put in place other standard controls will function normally to help prevent any brute forcing.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Limiting the number of operations that can be batched and run at once is another option to mitigate GraphQL batching attacks leading to DoS.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This is not a silver bullet though and should be used in conjunction with other methods.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] GraphQL Often comes by default with introspection and/or GraphiQL enabled and not requiring authentication.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This allows the consumer of your API to learn everything about your API, schemas, mutations, deprecated fields and sometimes unwanted "private fields".
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] This might be an intended configuration if your API is designed to be consumed by external clients, but can also be an issue if the API was designed to be used internally only.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Although security by obscurity is not recommended, it might be a good idea to consider removing the Introspection to avoid any leak.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] If your API is publicly consumed, you might want to consider disabling it for not authenticated or unauthorized users.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] For internal API, the easiest approach is to just disable introspection system-wide.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] See this page or consult your GraphQL implementation's documentation to learn how to disable introspection altogether.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] If your implementation does not natively support disabling introspection or if you would like to allow some consumers/roles to have this access, you can build a filter in your service to only allow approved consumers to access the introspection system.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Keep in mind that even if introspection is disabled, attackers can still guess fields by brute forcing them.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Furthermore, GraphQL has a built-in feature to return a hint when a field name that the requester provides is similar (but incorrect) to an existing field (*e.g.* request has `usr` and the response will ask `Did you mean "user?"`).
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] You should consider disabling this feature if you have disabled the introspection, to decrease the exposure, but not all implementations of GraphQL support doing so.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Shapeshifter is one tool that should be able to do this.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] GraphQL APIs in production shouldn't return stack traces or be in debug mode.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] Doing this is implementation specific, but using middleware is one popular way to have better control over errors the server returns.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] To disable excessive errors with Apollo Server, either pass `debug: false` to the Apollo Server constructor or set the `NODE_ENV` environment variable to 'production' or 'test'.
[src:graphql-security/graphql-cheat-sheet] However, if you would like to log the stack trace internally without returning it to the user see here for how to mask and log errors so they are available to the developers but not callers of the API.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] Facebook started GraphQL development in 2012 and released a draft specification and reference implementation as open source in 2015.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] In 2018, GraphQL was moved to the newly established GraphQL Foundation, hosted by the non-profit Linux Foundation.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] On February 9, 2018, the GraphQL Schema Definition Language became part of the specification.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] Many popular public APIs adopted GraphQL as the default way to access them.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] These include public APIs of Facebook, GitHub, Yelp, Shopify, Google Directions API and many others.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] There is an annual GraphQL Conference featuring new developments of the protocol and organizations successfully using GraphQL.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] The event is hosted by the GraphQL Foundation with previous organizers incl.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] GraphQL supports reading, writing (mutating), and subscribing to changes to data (realtime updates – commonly implemented using WebSockets).
[src:graphql-security/graphql] A GraphQL service is created by defining types with fields, then providing functions to resolve the data for each field.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] The types and fields make up what is known as the *schema definition*.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] The functions that retrieve and map the data are called *resolvers*.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] After being validated against the schema, a GraphQL query is executed by the server.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] The server returns a result that mirrors the shape of the original query, typically as JSON.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] With GraphQL, a business domain is modeled as a graph by defining a schema; within this schema, different types of nodes and their relations are defined.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] The GraphQL type system describes what data can be queried from the API.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] The collection of those capabilities is referred to as the service's *schema* and clients can use that schema to send queries to the API that return predictable results.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] The root type of a GraphQL schema, `Query` by default, contains all of the fields that can be queried.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] Other types define the objects and fields that the GraphQL server can return.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] There are several base types, called scalars, to represent things like strings, numbers, and IDs.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] Fields are defined as nullable by default, and a trailing exclamation mark can be used to make a field non-nullable (required).
[src:graphql-security/graphql] A field can be defined as a list by wrapping the field's type in square brackets (for example, `authors: [String]`).
[src:graphql-security/graphql] A GraphQL query defines the exact shape of the data needed by the client.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] Once validated and executed by the GraphQL server, the data is returned in the same shape.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] A GraphQL mutation allows for data to be created, updated, or deleted.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] Mutations generally contain *variables*, which allow data to be passed into the server from the client.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] The mutation also defines the shape of the data that will be returned to the client after the operation is complete.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] The variables are passed as an object with fields that match the variable names in the mutation.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] Once the operation is complete, the GraphQL server will return data matching the shape defined by the mutation.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] GraphQL also supports live updates sent from the server to client in an operation called a subscription.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] Again, the client defines the shape of the data that it needs whenever an update is made.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] When a mutation is made through the GraphQL server that updates the associated field, data is sent to all subscribed clients in the format setup through the subscription.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] While there's nothing that prevents a GraphQL service from being versioned just like any other API, GraphQL takes a strong opinion on avoiding versioning by providing the tools for the continuous evolution of a GraphQL schema.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] The `@deprecated` *built-in directive* is used within the type system definition language to indicate deprecated portions of a GraphQL service's schema, such as deprecated fields on a type or deprecated enum values.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] GraphQL only returns the data that's explicitly requested, so new capabilities can be added via new types or new fields on existing types without creating a breaking change.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] This has led to a common practice of always avoiding breaking changes and serving a versionless API.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] GraphQL does not provide a full-fledged graph query language such as SPARQL, or even in dialects of SQL that support transitive closure.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] For example, a GraphQL interface that reports the parents of an individual cannot return, in a single query, the set of all their ancestors.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] GraphQL APIs can be tested manually or with automated tools issuing GraphQL requests and verifying the correctness of the results.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] Automatic test generation is also possible.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] New requests may be produced through search-based techniques due to a typed schema and introspection capabilities.
[src:graphql-security/graphql] Some of the software tools used for testing GraphQL implementations include Postman, Beeceptor, GraphiQL, Apollo Studio, GraphQL Hive, GraphQL Editor, and Step CI.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:graphql-security/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:graphql-security/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:graphql-security/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:graphql-security/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:graphql-security/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:graphql-security/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:graphql-security/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:graphql-security/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:graphql-security/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:graphql-security/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:graphql-security/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:graphql-security/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:graphql-security/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:graphql-security/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:graphql-security/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:graphql-security/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:graphql-security/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:graphql-security/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:graphql-security/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:graphql-security/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:graphql-security/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:graphql-security/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:graphql-security/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:graphql-security/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:graphql-security/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:graphql-security/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:graphql-security/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:graphql-security/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:graphql-security/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:graphql-security/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:graphql-security/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:graphql-security/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:graphql-security/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:graphql-security/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:graphql-security/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:graphql-security/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:graphql-security/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:graphql-security/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:graphql-security/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:graphql-security/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:graphql-security/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:graphql-security/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:graphql-security/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:graphql-security/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:graphql-security/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:graphql-security/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:graphql-security/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:graphql-security/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:graphql-security/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:graphql-security/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:graphql-security/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:graphql-security/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:graphql-security/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:graphql-security/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:graphql-security/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:graphql-security/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:graphql-security/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:graphql-security/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:graphql-security/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:graphql-security/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:graphql-security/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:graphql-security/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:graphql-security/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:graphql-security/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:graphql-security/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:graphql-security/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:graphql-security/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:graphql-security/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:graphql-security/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:graphql-security/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:graphql-security/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:graphql-security/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:graphql-security/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:graphql-security/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:graphql-security/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:graphql-security/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:graphql-security/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:graphql-security/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:graphql-security/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:graphql-security/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:graphql-security/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:graphql-security/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:graphql-security/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:graphql-security/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:graphql-security/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:graphql-security/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:graphql-security/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:graphql-security/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:graphql-security/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:graphql-security/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:graphql-security/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:graphql-security/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
